{% extends "_layouts/base.twig" %}

{% block title %}Styleguide · {{ siteName }}{% endblock %}

{% block body %}

<section>
    <div class="contain p-12">
<div class="prose">

                    <h1>The quick brown fox jumps over the lazy dog</h1>

                    <p class="lead">This is an introduction paragraph, the kind that sits below an h1 and sets the tone for the article. It
                        contains a mix of <strong>strong emphasis</strong>, <em>italic emphasis</em>, and <a href="#">a link to
                            somewhere</a>. The typography system handles all three consistently.</p>

                    <p>A second paragraph, because one is rarely enough to establish rhythm. Notice the spacing between
                        paragraphs versus the spacing before the next heading — the heading sits closer to the content it
                        introduces than to the section above.</p>

                    <p>A third paragraph continues the thought, giving the reader a chance to settle into the measure before
                        the first subheading arrives. Long-form content lives or dies on this kind of quiet pacing — the
                        invisible scaffolding that lets the eye travel without snagging. If a paragraph feels dense, it usually
                        isn't the words; it's the leading, the measure, or the contrast.</p>

                    <h2>A secondary heading</h2>

                    <p>Secondary headings introduce major shifts in topic without resetting the reader's orientation the way an
                        h1 would. They carry roughly the weight of a chapter subsection — large enough to command attention,
                        small enough to belong to the article rather than crown it.</p>

                    <p>Body copy continues. Here's an unordered list:</p>

                    <ul>
                        <li>First item in the list</li>
                        <li>Second item, slightly longer to show how multi-line list items wrap and breathe</li>
                        <li>
                            Third item with nested children:
                            <ul>
                                <li>A nested item</li>
                                <li>Another nested item</li>
                            </ul>
                        </li>
                        <li>Fourth item back at the top level</li>
                    </ul>

                    <h3>A tertiary heading</h3>

                    <p>Sometimes you want to reference code inline — like <code>display: grid</code> or
                        <code>var(--prose-base)</code> — and the typography treats it as a small visual token within the
                        sentence.</p>

                    <p>Inline elements compose without friction: abbreviations like <abbr title="Cascading Style Sheets">CSS</abbr>
                        sit beside <kbd>⌘</kbd>&nbsp;<kbd>K</kbd> keystrokes, sample output in <samp>→ 200 OK</samp>, and
                        mathematical variables like <var>x</var> and <var>y</var>, each taking their cue from the surrounding
                        sentence rather than announcing themselves.</p>

                    <h3>Definition lists</h3>

                    <p>Definition lists are a quietly useful format for glossaries, key-value pairs, and short-form
                        specifications. They're rarely styled thoughtfully, which makes them a good litmus test for a
                        typography system.</p>

                    <dl>
                        <dt>Measure</dt>
                        <dd>The length of a line of type, typically between 45 and 75 characters for comfortable reading.</dd>

                        <dt>Leading</dt>
                        <dd>The vertical space between lines of type, usually expressed as a multiple of the font size.</dd>

                        <dt>Tracking</dt>
                        <dd>The horizontal space applied uniformly across a run of characters — distinct from kerning, which
                            adjusts individual pairs.</dd>
                    </dl>

                    <blockquote>
                        <p>Typography is the craft of endowing human language with a durable visual form. It is the most
                            important part of graphic design — because it is the one part that readers actually read.</p>
                    </blockquote>

                    <p>Block quotes sit between paragraphs with their own visual weight, and for longer quotes they can span
                        multiple paragraphs without losing the left-border treatment.</p>

                    <blockquote>
                        <p>Good typography is invisible. Bad typography is everywhere. The reader should notice the argument,
                            not the apparatus that carries it.</p>
                        <p>This is why the defaults matter more than the flourishes — most of the words on most of the pages
                            will be set in the body style, and every decision there compounds.</p>
                    </blockquote>

                    <h3>Ordered lists and code blocks</h3>

                    <ol>
                        <li>First step in a process</li>
                        <li>Second step, with more detail to show how numbered items handle wrapping</li>
                        <li>Third and final step</li>
                    </ol>

                    <pre><code>// A code block for longer snippets
function greet(name) {
    return `Hello, ${name}`;
}

greet("World");</code></pre>

                    <p>Code blocks handle horizontal overflow cleanly for long lines, and use a subtle background to distinguish
                        them from body copy without overwhelming the page.</p>

                    <h3>Tables</h3>

                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Column one</th>
                                <th>Column two</th>
                                <th>Column three</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Cell content</td>
                                <td>More cell content</td>
                                <td>Even more</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Second row</td>
                                <td>Second row data</td>
                                <td>Final cell</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Third row</td>
                                <td>More data</td>
                                <td>Last value</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>

                    <h3>Figures and captions</h3>

                    <p>Figures bundle an image, diagram, or embed together with a caption that describes or credits it. The
                        caption sits tightly under its figure and reads as a secondary voice — smaller, quieter, slightly
                        muted.</p>

                    <figure>
                        <svg viewBox="0 0 800 360" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" role="img" aria-label="Placeholder figure" style="width:100%;height:auto;display:block;background:#f1f5f9;border-radius:4px;">
                            <defs>
                                <pattern id="stripes" width="12" height="12" patternUnits="userSpaceOnUse" patternTransform="rotate(45)">
                                    <rect width="12" height="12" fill="#f1f5f9"></rect>
                                    <line x1="0" y1="0" x2="0" y2="12" stroke="#cbd5e1" stroke-width="6"></line>
                                </pattern>
                            </defs>
                            <rect width="800" height="360" fill="url(#stripes)"></rect>
                            <text x="400" y="186" text-anchor="middle" font-family="ui-monospace, Menlo, monospace" font-size="14" fill="#475569">[ figure placeholder — 800 × 360 ]</text>
                        </svg>
                        <figcaption>Figure 1. A placeholder illustration, sized to the prose measure and captioned below.</figcaption>
                    </figure>

                    <hr>

                    <p>A horizontal rule marks a stronger break than a heading does — useful for separating distinct sections
                        within a long article. A final paragraph closes things out, demonstrating the <code>:last-child</code>
                        margin reset that prevents trailing whitespace below the last element.</p>

                </div>
    </div>
</section>


{# Size variants. Overriding --prose-base on a descendant rescales the
   entire modular scale — headings, lead, captions, list markers all follow.
   Stacked here at the same container width so the proportions are directly
   comparable. #}
<section>
    <div class="contain p-12 space-y-16">

        <div class="prose">
            <h2>Size variants</h2>
            <p class="lead">The module exposes three size variants — <code>.prose-sm</code>, <code>.prose-lg</code>, <code>.prose-xl</code> — that rescale the entire modular scale by overriding <code>--prose-base</code>. Heading sizes, body text, the lead bump, captions, and list markers all follow proportionally. Each variant below sits at the same container width, so the relative sizing is the test.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="prose prose-sm">
            <h3>Small — <code>.prose-sm</code> (0.875rem base)</h3>
            <p class="lead">Lead paragraph. At the smaller base, the subtle 1.125× bump still reads as "this is the opening" without pulling disproportionate attention.</p>
            <p>Body paragraph. Suited to sidebars, dense product listings, and secondary content where the reading load is light and screen real estate is at a premium.</p>
            <ul>
                <li>List markers scale with the base</li>
                <li>Indent and marker size follow the rem anchor</li>
            </ul>
            <p><small>Small text for captions and footnotes, one modular step below body.</small></p>
        </div>

        <div class="prose">
            <h3>Default — <code>.prose</code> (1rem base)</h3>
            <p class="lead">Lead paragraph. The reference size — most article body content lives here, and every other size variant is a deviation from this.</p>
            <p>Body paragraph at the anchor rem. Standard article reading, blog posts, documentation, CMS-rendered content with no special context.</p>
            <ul>
                <li>The modular scale's reference rung</li>
                <li>Everything else derives from this</li>
            </ul>
            <p><small>Small text at one modular step below the base.</small></p>
        </div>

        <div class="prose prose-lg">
            <h3>Large — <code>.prose-lg</code> (1.125rem base)</h3>
            <p class="lead">Lead paragraph. A touch more air across the scale suits editorial pieces where the reading experience itself is part of the offer.</p>
            <p>Body paragraph at 1.125rem. Magazine-style articles, longreads, feature content — anywhere the type wants to feel more considered.</p>
            <ul>
                <li>Everything rescales in proportion</li>
                <li>Em-based spacing follows the new base</li>
            </ul>
            <p><small>Small text bumps up accordingly, maintaining the one-step offset.</small></p>
        </div>

        <div class="prose prose-xl">
            <h3>Extra large — <code>.prose-xl</code> (1.25rem base)</h3>
            <p class="lead">Lead paragraph. Hero copy, feature pieces, landing sections — when the page itself is the content, keep passages short.</p>
            <p>Body paragraph at 1.25rem. The scale still uses the 1.25 ratio, so headings rise proportionally with the base without recalibration.</p>
            <ul>
                <li>Spacing remains proportional at this size</li>
                <li>Headings can feel dominant — use sparingly</li>
            </ul>
            <p><small>Caption size at the top of the range, still readable as secondary text.</small></p>
        </div>

    </div>
</section>


