{# Combined variants. .prose-white (colour) and .prose-sm / .prose-lg
   (size) apply independently and should stack cleanly. This is the test
   that variant composition works — colour tokens come from one class,
   scale tokens from another. #}
<section class="bg-neutral-900">
    <div class="contain p-12 space-y-16">

        <div class="prose prose-white">
            <h2>Combined variants</h2>
            <p class="lead">Colour and size variants compose. <code>.prose-white</code> supplies the reversed palette; <code>.prose-sm</code> or <code>.prose-lg</code> supplies the scale. Applied together on a container, both effects land without conflict.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="prose prose-white prose-sm">
            <h3>Small on dark — <code>.prose prose-white prose-sm</code></h3>
            <p class="lead">Lead at the small base, white on dark. Muted blockquote text, white links, and softened borders all follow the colour variant while the size variant holds.</p>
            <blockquote>
                <p>Reversed type at smaller sizes asks for a little extra care. Leading and weight can't fully do what light-on-dark contrast used to — the muted treatment still reads, just quieter.</p>
            </blockquote>
            <p>Body text with inline <code>code</code> on a translucent white wash, and <a href="#">a link treated as in the light variant</a> but anchored to white.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="prose prose-white prose-lg">
            <h3>Large on dark — <code>.prose prose-white prose-lg</code></h3>
            <p class="lead">Lead at the large base, white on dark. Longer passages get room to breathe — the leading stays honest even under reversed contrast, and the scale lifts without the colour variant needing adjustment.</p>
            <blockquote>
                <p>Type on dark reads tighter than on light at the same nominal size. The larger scale compensates, and the muted treatment — here a 70% white — still carries the secondary-voice signal the quote wants.</p>
            </blockquote>
            <p>Body text at the larger scale, with <code>inline code</code> and <a href="#">links that remain readable</a>. Variant composition comes through unchanged — only the cascading tokens differ.</p>
        </div>

    </div>
</section>

{% endblock %}
